# infra/hyperevm-mainnet/.env — Ophis HyperEVM mainnet secrets.
# COPY this file to .env, fill in the secrets, NEVER COMMIT the populated form.
# .gitignore already excludes infra/hyperevm-mainnet/.env.
#
# After copying, chmod 600 .env — render-configs.sh enforces this on every
# deploy but the initial copy is on the operator.
#
# NOTE (2026-05-18, Tier 1 PK isolation): the driver-submitter PK is no
# longer stored in the macOS Keychain or this .env file. It lives at
# /Users/ophis-driver/.config/submitter.key (0600, owned by ophis-driver
# user). The OPHIS_DRIVER_SUBMITTER_KEY var below is retained for
# template completeness but should be left empty in production .env;
# render-configs.sh threads the file-based PK directly to driver.toml.

# ── Database ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Pick a strong random password (32+ chars). Generate via:
#   openssl rand -base64 32
POSTGRES_USER=ophis
POSTGRES_PASSWORD=
POSTGRES_DB=ophis
DB_WRITE_URL=postgresql://ophis:${POSTGRES_PASSWORD}@db:5432/ophis
DB_READ_URL=postgresql://ophis:${POSTGRES_PASSWORD}@db:5432/ophis

# ── Chain RPC ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Alchemy HyperEVM mainnet endpoint. The public RPC (rpc.hyperliquid.xyz/evm)
# caps at 100 req/min/IP which the driver would blow through quickly. Alchemy
# free tier is 30M CU/month — plenty for early launch volume. Retrieve key:
#   security find-generic-password -s alchemy-api-key -w
ALCHEMY_API_KEY=
HYPEREVM_MAINNET_RPC=https://hyperliquid-mainnet.g.alchemy.com/v2/${ALCHEMY_API_KEY}

# ── Driver-submitter private key ──────────────────────────────────────────
# Corresponds to on-chain address 0x92B9bE5e96795E8630fDC61efb0e705E75b1A1B1
# (post-rotation EOA, same as OP + MegaETH). Must be allowlisted on the
# Ophis AllowList for chain 999 via deploy-mainnet-all.sh Step 3.
#
# Pre-deploy: this EOA must also be opted into HyperEVM big blocks via
# infra/hyperevm/opt-in-big-blocks.py — settle() exceeds the 3M-gas
# small-block limit so without opt-in the tx never lands.
#
# DEPRECATED post-Tier-1 PK isolation (2026-05-18). The PK now lives at
# /Users/ophis-driver/.config/submitter.key and is read by render-configs.sh
# directly. Leave this var empty in production .env.
OPHIS_DRIVER_SUBMITTER_KEY=

# ── OKX V6 aggregator: NOT USED on chain 999 ──────────────────────────────
# OKX does not yet support HyperEVM (verified 2026-05-15). When they do,
# re-add OKX_PROJECT_ID / OKX_API_KEY / OKX_SECRET_KEY / OKX_PASSPHRASE
# from infra/optimism-mainnet/.env.example and uncomment the okx-solver
# service in docker-compose.yml.

# ── HyperSwap V3 subgraph (baseline solver UniV3 liquidity) ───────────────
# Default in render-configs.sh is the Ormi-hosted public subgraph
# (verified-live 2026-05-16: 2610 indexed pools, current block, no errors):
#   https://api.subgraph.ormilabs.com/api/public/33c67399-d625-4929-b239-5709cd66e422/subgraphs/hyperswap-v3/v0.1.2/gn
#
# Override only if you've stood up a self-hosted Goldsky / graph-node
# instance. Leave unset to use the Ormi default — render-configs.sh
# fills it in via the `:=` default operator.
#
# HOW TO DISABLE (sharp-edges audit, 2026-05-17): setting this variable
# to empty string here will NOT disable the HyperSwap V3 liquidity
# source. Because render-configs.sh uses `:=` (substitute if unset OR
# empty), an empty value silently rehydrates to the Ormi default. To
# actually disable the source, COMMENT OUT the matching
# [[liquidity.uniswap-v3]] block in configs/driver.toml.tmpl and
# re-render. There is no env-only kill switch by design.
#
# HYPERSWAP_V3_SUBGRAPH_URL=

# ── Alertmanager → Telegram (observability stack) ─────────────────────────
# Bot token for @clawdiusfranciscus_bot (Clement's bot). Source of truth
# in macOS Keychain not yet set up; current authoritative location is:
#   python3 -c "import json;print(json.load(open('/Users/scep/.kimi/kimi-claw/openclaw.json'))['channels']['telegram']['botToken'])"
# (originally at ~/.openclaw/openclaw.json — moved to ~/.kimi/kimi-claw/
# when OpenClaw gateway was decommissioned. Reference memory:
# reference_telegram_bot_token.md).
#
# Format check: render-configs.sh validates `{int}:{base64-ish}` shape.
#
# At render time the token is written to chmod-600 file
# observability-rendered/telegram-token and mounted into the
# alertmanager container as /etc/alertmanager/telegram-token. NOT passed
# as env var to alertmanager — avoids `docker inspect` leak.
TELEGRAM_BOT_TOKEN=
